<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-746-715  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 746 715.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  July 1989 v62 n7 p46(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Technology vs. terror. (includes related article on El Al'ssecurity system and plastic explosives' imperviousness to X-raydetection)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Flanagan, Patrick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>New technology is being developed for the airline industry for thedetection of weapons and explosives.andP;  The emphasis of thetechnology is on detecting explosives in checked and carry-onbaggage.andP;  These new technologies fall into two categories.andP;  Vapordetection devices sniff the air, setting off an alarm when achemical element found in explosives is detected.andP;  Thermalneutron-activation (TNA) devices sense characteristic gammaradiation from chemical elements.andP;  The Federal AviationAdministration has already purchased six TNA units.andP;  One such unitis Science Applications International Corp's system for nuclearobservation of possible explosives (SNOOPE).andP;  With SNOOPE, a pieceof luggage up to 16 inches wide and 26 inches deep, and of anylength, enters a 13-foot-long device on a conveyor belt.andP;  An alarmsounds when possible explosives are detected.andP;  Other detectionsystems are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Airline IndustrySecurityScanningApplicationsDetectors.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartphotograph.andO;Caption:   Science Applications International Corp's Snoope analyzer. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>